<HEAD>Party Faithful Take Time to Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Sunday evening parties;
PICKS UP 6th graf pvs bgng, `The biggest'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The air-conditioned walkway was the extravagance most appreciated by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> political leaders and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> media elite lingering by the mock newsstand bars at the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> newspapers' welcoming party Sunday night. `` Even the <ORGANIZATION> Ringling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>' tent is n't air conditioned,'' one guest marveled at the <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> party on the eve of the Democratic National Convention. Dozens of invitation-only affairs and 56 parties for individual state delegations kept thousands of delegates and journalists entertained on the hot and humid day. Prospective Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his family attended <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s crowded party at <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, next door to the convention site, before joining a family reunion hosted by his cousin, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> restaurateur <PERSON> Pano </PERSON> <PERSON> Karatassos </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, dining at a separate party at <PERSON> Karatassos </PERSON>' 103 West, stopped by to greet the families of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his vice presidential choice, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s fans jammed the ornate Fox Theater for a fund-raising jazz and gospel concert, listening to music by <PERSON> Nat </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>'s brother <PERSON> Freddie </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> resident, and others for three hours before <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and his family arrived to rally the faithful. Frigid air pumped into a tent spanning the short walkway between the <ORGANIZATION> Woodruff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and the High Museum of Art cooled the 3,000 politicians and media honchos attending `` A Special Edition Of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitality </ORGANIZATION>,'' hosted by the parent company for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> and The Atlanta Constitution. The media chain, founded by 1920 Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, apparently spared little expense for its party, filling the tent and the lobbies of both buildings with bars and tables overflowing with home-grown delicacies such as peach cheesecake. Sunday's partying completed a weekend of carousing by about 35,000 journalists, lobbyists, staffers, elected officials and political junkies who have descended on <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> for the convention, which opens Monday. All night Saturday, hotels were hopping, bars were packed and lines extended out of dozens of nightclubs and restaurants along <LOCATION> Peachtree </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> long past the normal closing time of 2 a.m. The horse-drawn carriages in the downtown hotel district were doing a booming business as hundreds of people wandered streets normally occupied in the early morning hours by the now-scarce homeless. An overflow crowd from a heavy metal nightclub spilled onto nearby railroad tracks, halting a train loaded with revelers. But neither party missed a beat as the train retreated. Private parties ranged from a formal dinner-dance at the home of <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and chairwoman of <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, to an old fashioned `` stump speakin''' with a real stump, mint juleps and ham biscuits, given by <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Talmadge </PERSON>, former wife of former Sen. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Talmadge </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Liz </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, former press secretary to <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. The biggest affair was a rock' n' roll extravaganza for about 10,000 journalists at the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, featuring plenty of free liquor and dozens of dishes, ranging from hot dogs and egg rolls to <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> stew and jambalaya. Bandstands scattered throughout the huge exhibition hall showcased such acts as jazz artist <PERSON> Grover </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, rhythm-and-blues duo <PERSON> Ashford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> and folk rocker <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stills </PERSON>. In a brief greeting, Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> extended a special welcome to the kid reporters for the Children's Express, whom he called `` the only uncorrupted, honest, unbiased'' journalists in the hall. Clearly he had missed seeing the Express reporter who raided a fruit display, plopping whole pineapples into a plastic bag. `` We might get hungry later,'' the boy said. <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s black community hosted a party for more than 250 black elected officials from across the country at the white-columned mansion of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldston </PERSON>. Many of those revelers then joined former <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on his `` Midnight Train To <LOCATION> Georgia </LO