<SECOND>AM-Snail Hunt, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snails Sought To Revive Ancient Ritual</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Orthodox Jews are scouring <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> beaches for a rare snail that produces a blue dye they say is needed to revive a religious ritual abandoned 1,500 years ago The snail hunt was prompted last week by Rabbi <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, who is trying to recreate a process once used to dye a single thread of the Jewish prayer shawl in accordance with a biblical command. Jews were forced to abandon the practice in the fifth century, <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON> said, when Roman authorities banned all but the ruling class from wearing colored clothing. The recipe for the dye they used was lost. `` Now we are looking for it,'' said <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON>, of the prestigious Mercaz Harav religious seminary. `` We want to revive the mitzva -LRB- biblical command -RRB-.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s chief rabbis, who rule on religious issues, have not given the go-ahead to renew the ancient practice and are awaiting <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON>'s findings before they consider it, said <PERSON> Zalman </PERSON> <PERSON> Quittner </PERSON>, a spokesman for the rabbis. Interest in the mollusk mystery was roused when <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON> appealed in a religious newspaper, `` Erev Shabat,'' for seminary students to seek out the rare snail, known as the Janthina or `` violet snail'' because of its purple-blue color. <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON> said he has been deluged with reports of snail sightings. But he has so far collected only a tenth of the `` bucketful'' he says is needed to extract enough dye to test his theory. The 33-year-old rabbi is trying to validate a claim made in 1920 by the late Chief Rabbi <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Halevy </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON>, father of President <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON>. In a doctoral thesis at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>, the elder <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> suggested the original dye used came from the Janthina snail. But he noted the the snail seldom made it to <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> shores. This summer, however, the snails have been sighted along with schools of jellyfish that have been plaguing beaches, <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Mienis </PERSON>, curator of the <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mollusk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collection </ORGANIZATION>, said there are five species of the Janthina. The largest are 1 -LCB- inches in diameter, he said. The ancient Jewish practice involved coloring one of eight strands of a prayer shawl as a sign of devotion to God. The white prayer shawls have been worn under clothing by devout Jewish men since the ancient Israelites roamed the desert with <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> during their exodus from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. It is customary to kiss one of the fringes during portions of morning prayers. The Old Testament says that God ordered Moses: `` Speak to the children of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and tell them to make for themselves fringes on the corners of their garments throughout their generations, and to put on the fringe of each corner a blue thread. `` You shall have it as a fringe, so that when you look upon it you will remember to do all the commands of the Lord, and you will not follow the desires of your heart and your eyes which lead you astray.'' The Talmud, which interprets Jewish law, explained how the blue fringe should be dyed but did not give the source of the dye. Jewish sages have speculated about the recipe, but only began trying to revive the custom about 100 years ago in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON> said. He said a Hasidic rabbi, <PERSON> Gershon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanoch </PERSON> <PERSON> Leiner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Radzin </LOCATION>, maintained the dye came from a squid. About 17,000 followers of <PERSON> Leiner </PERSON> used the method, he said, and many died at the hands of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> during World War II. <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> differed with <PERSON> Leiner </PERSON>'s followers by suggesting the Janthina snail, and not the squid, was the true source of the dye. `` I am checking <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON>'s method to the end,'' said <PERSON> Burstin </PERSON>, who has been studying the issue for 14 years. `` We can not push this mitzva forward until we solve this.''
