<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bus braking to avoid three cows crossing a road was struck in the rear by another bus in foggy weather Sunday and 38 people were killed, police reported. They said dozens of passengers were injured in the accident but they did not have the exact figure. The bus that was rear-ended went off the road and into a lake and many of the victims drowned when they were trapped in the partially submerged vehicle, according to police. They said all of the bodies were recovered and there were no foreigners on either bus. All of the people who perished were on the first bus that was carrying 50 passengers, according to the television network <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globo </ORGANIZATION>. It said there were 45 passengers aboard the second bus. Police spokesman <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> said the buses were making the 335-mile trip from <LOCATION> Londrina </LOCATION> in the southern state of <LOCATION> Parana </LOCATION> to an industrical center near <LOCATION> Campinas </LOCATION> when the accident occurred. `` It was early morning, foggy and the road is narrow,'' said <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> who was contacted by telephone in <LOCATION> Piracicaba </LOCATION>, a town 165 miles west of <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION> and near the site of the accident. `` Three cows crossed the road, the first driver braked suddenly and the second smashed into the back of the bus, pushing the first vehicle into a roadside lake,'' <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> said. He said both bus drivers survived.
