<FIRST>r f AM-AIDS-Insurance     07-17 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Insurance,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Insurance Companies: AIDS Screenings Help Pinpoint Other Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some insurance companies say that testing more applicants for exposure to AIDS has benefited the industry by helping identify other applicant health problems, such as cocaine use and diabetes. Life and health insurers are using the opportunity offered by increased AIDS testing to perform more general screenings on the blood and urine of applicants. When abnormal readings turn up, insurers sometimes deny applications for coverage or charge higher premiums, industry officials said. `` AIDS is the best thing that ever happened to the life-insurance industry,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Richman </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Plainville </LOCATION>. `` It's the best thing as far as underwriting. Insurance companies can now underwrite with much more information.'' Until recent years, a consumer could buy several hundred thousand dollars of life insurance by answering medical questions on an application, without submitting to blood or urine tests. But with growing concern about acquired immune deficiency syndrome, companies began requiring AIDS antibody tests of applicants for amounts of life insurance above certain threshholds, commonly $ 100,000 worth of insurance. Insurers also often require AIDS tests of people applying for individual health policies. Travelers, for instance, requires the tests for most of its individual health policies. Companies will not insure people with positive AIDS antibody test results because of the increased likelihood they will develop the syndrome, and they will not insure cocaine users. When insurers require blood to be drawn for an AIDS tests, they generally have a laboratory screen it for other problems, and also order a urine test. A typical blood and urine screening costs the insurer $ 50 to $ 75 per person, said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, an associate counsel at <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. The lab checks blood for sugar levels, fats and protein and looks for signs of cardiovascular disease, liver and kidney disorders. Companies also are checking urine for nicotine, to verify whether people who say they are non-smokers are telling the truth, and for problems associated with heavy drinking. <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> said it is rejecting about 3 percent of applications for individual life insurance, compared with 2 percent two years ago, but <PERSON> Testa </PERSON> was not sure how much of the increase is due to increased blood testing. <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> would not say how often it denies applications because of positive AIDS tests and said it did not track denials for other medical causes. Travelers said testing is revealing more conditions that warrant higher rates or rejection of an applicant. But spokesman <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bushnell </PERSON> said that when an insurer knows it is discovering more of its customers' problems through tests, its rates will reflect fewer cost for unknown risks. `` If we can better classify people's mortality risk, actuaries can sharpen their pencils in terms of pricing,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. `` The better we can underwrite, the more narrowly we can price, and everyone's better off.''
